@bolkedebruin, the CI process isn't stable. 
==============New===========================
p.s. please re-run the ci process, since it worked for my repository.

@mistercrunch You mean.. to disable a pool across multiple DAGs in order to indicate that a resource is down? I can see that use-case. 

However, It's hacky. I propose a different approach :  a UI control called `Enable/Disable Pool` backed by a new boolean column in the pool table and a check in the scheduler for this case.  The problem with setting the value from N to 0 is remembering what N was when you need to reset it.

Additionally, as mentioned, it's already bitten us in production. I prefer stricter aka less ambiguous failure semantics around this.

@bolkedebruin and @r39132 - I finally was able to figure out what the issue was (turns out using DagRun to get previous TI only works if there IS a dag run (so not on backfill, go figure) so that minor change that I agreed to for Bolke turned out to be an issue.

Tracked that down and the tests are now passing.

Please review ASAP.
